seasonOutlook: Abbott was limited to 25 starts after his season ended in mid-August due to a strained shoulder, but he's expected to be healthy for spring training. His 3.72 ERA is misleading as shown by a less impressive 4.91 xFIP and 4.78 SIERA. A high 82.9% left on base mark rescued his season. Abbott's strikeout rate plummeted to 19.5%, down from 26.1% in his rookie season. His velocity and repertoire didn't change, so perhaps Abbott needs to be less predictable with his sequencing. He's slated to be in the Reds rotation, but unless he regains lost dominance, Abbott's ratios are vulnerable, particularly at home in Great American Ballpark.

Abrams appeared in only 138 games last season, but half of the missed time occurred in September when he missed out on the last eight games of the season after being demoted to Triple-A for staying out all night prior to a day game. Despite a second-half swoon, Abrams improved his hard-hit rate overall and experienced an uptick in power. The added production helped mitigate a drop in steals. In 2023, Abrams swiped 47 bags in 51 tries for an outstanding 92 percent success rate. Last season, he was just 31-for-43 (72 percent). Still just 24 years old, Abrams is expected to learn from last season's disciplinary action and continue maturing as a person and player. The arrows are pointing upward, especially if he can cut down on last season's caught stealing number.

Abreu is the only reliever in baseball to have struck out 100 or more batters out of the bullpen in each of the past two seasons, joining teammate Josh Hader as well as Fernando Cruz and Mason Miller in that club for 2024. Abreu could challenge for saves on most other clubs, but as long as he and Hader are teammates, Abreu appears to be the Robin to Hader's Batman. Abreu has the highest strikeout rate among all non-closing relievers over the past three seasons, and those strikeouts and stellar ratios make Abreu an interesting play in deep formats. The risk comes in the fact that so few relievers ever work 70-plus innings over consecutive seasons let alone three as Abreu will likely be asked to do with Houston dealing Ryan Pressly away this winter.

Abreu's impressive minor-league performances in 2022 and 203 got him on some radars, and his first full season of big-league play had its moments. Abreu didn't steal bases like he did in 2022 when he stole 31 bags in Double-A nor did he reach base at a .390 clip as he did between Triple-A and the majors in 2023, but Abreu was a monster against righties, slashing .266/.334/.491 with 14 of his 15 homers. His production against righties was 26 percent above league average, but that all changed against southpaws. His struggles against left-handed pitching are why the likes of Rob Refsnyder persists on the Boston depth chart as the duo make a solid tandem while the club tries to figure out whether Abreu can handle lefties or is destined for a strong-side platoon future like many lefties before him.

Acuna's seven-year MLB career has been quite the rollercoaster ride. He has won NL Rookie of the Year (2018) and MVP Awards (2023). He's had a 41/37 campaign (2019) and the majors' first-ever 40/70 season (2023) on his rsum, yet has also dealt with three separate ACL injuries (among other ailments) including surgeries on both of his knees (the right in 2021, the left in 2024). Fantasy managers should heed Acuna's performance initially returning from surgery the last time, as he missed the first three weeks of 2022 while recovering, then finished 65th on the Player Rater and tied for 175th in fantasy points scored. A sluggish start could be his downside -- tuck that away as a strategic nugget to perhaps instead trade for him in-season -- but his upside remains that of a five-category rotisserie superstar. If reports on his health during spring training look good, he shouldn't slide much further than the first couple of rounds of rotisserie drafts, nor far outside the top-25 overall in points leagues.

Adam has been on a three-year tear since being plucked by the Rays off the free-agent wire when the Cubs didn't see what they had. He has shown the ability to step in for saves when needed as well as contribute to all five pitching categories. Adam's success comes from his ability to throw four different pitch types to both righties and lefties, and he will use any of his pitches at any time. This past season saw him improve his slider which was downright unhittable. Adam's .162 batting average against over the past three seasons leads all relievers with at least 150 innings pitched over that span, and he is 10 points lower than any other pitcher on that list. Robert Suarez is still the favorite for saves in San Diego, but Adam has value as a late-inning weapon and his value skyrockets should anything happen with Suarez.

Adames parlayed what was a career year on many fronts into a seven-year, $182 million contract with the Giants -- one of the offseason's earliest signings. He'll now play in a more challenging hitting environment than during his three and a half years in Milwaukee. Playing in the Brewers' HR-friendly home ballpark, Adames managed personal bests with his 32 home runs, 112 RBI, 93 runs scored, 153 hits, 33 doubles, 21 stolen bases, 74 walks and 282 total bases last season, while also pacing all major leaguers with 224 plate appearances and 93 RBI with runners in scoring position. The park switch assures some regression in the power departments, as does the good fortune in the RBI column. Nevertheless, Adames is a prime-age hitter who should put forth top-10 positional numbers in all fantasy formats.

Albies is a three-time All-Star and two-time Silver Slugger, but injuries have kept him under 100 games played in two of the past three seasons. First, a fractured right toe put him on the shelf last year before a fractured left wrist cost him most of the summer. There was some uncertainty as to whether he would return last season, but Albies made it back for nine games at the very end of the campaign. In addition to the injuries, there have been chirps that Albies could or perhaps should give up switch hitting given his career splits as a left-handed hitter against right-handed pitching (.247/.309/.434). Despite the flaws in his profile, Albies is arguably still right up there among the top second basemen on the board, maybe behind only Ketel Marte. As he enters his age-28 season, Albies will be attempting to turn the page on his recent health woes and return to 30-10 production for Atlanta.
